  '<h2 id="dkim">DKIM signing <a class="anchor" href="#dkim">#</a></h2>',
  '<p><code>b.mail.dkim</code> generates a <code>DKIM-Signature</code> header on outbound mail per RFC 6376 (default <code>rsa-sha256</code>) or RFC 8463 (opt-in <code>ed25519-sha256</code>). The signer is wired into the SMTP transport via <code>dkimSigner</code>; vendor-API transports (Resend, generic HTTP) rely on the provider\'s own sender-domain authentication. The <code>a=</code> tag carries the algorithm identifier so future post-quantum DKIM (when an SLH-DSA / ML-DSA variant is standardized) slots into the same envelope without breaking the public surface.</p>',
  '<h3>b.mail.dkim.create(opts)</h3>',
  '<pre><code class="language-javascript">{',
  '  domain:            string,               // required: true',
  '  selector:          string,               // required: true — published at <selector>._domainkey.<domain>',
  '  privateKey:        string | KeyObject,   // required: true — PEM or KeyObject',
  '  algorithm:         "rsa-sha256" | "ed25519-sha256",',
  '                                           // default: "rsa-sha256"',
  '  headersToSign:     string[],             // default: ["from","to","subject","date","message-id"]',
  '  canonicalization:  "relaxed/relaxed" | "simple/simple" | ...,',
  '                                           // default: "relaxed/relaxed"',
  '  bodyLength:        number,               // default: null — sign first N bytes (l= tag)',
  '  audit:             AuditTap,              // default: null',
  '}</code></pre>',
  '<pre><code class="language-javascript">var signer = b.mail.dkim.create({',
  '  domain:     "example.com",',
  '  selector:   "s1",',
  '  privateKey: env("DKIM_PRIVATE_KEY"),  // PEM string or KeyObject',
  '  algorithm:  "rsa-sha256",             // or "ed25519-sha256"',
  '});',
  '',
  'var mail = b.mail.create({',
  '  transport: b.mail.transports.smtp({',
  '    host:       "smtp.example.com",',
  '    port:       587,',
  '    dkimSigner: signer,',
  '  }),',
  '});</code></pre>',
  '<p>Selectors are published in DNS as TXT records at <code>&lt;selector&gt;._domainkey.&lt;domain&gt;</code>. Headers signed by default: <code>from</code>, <code>to</code>, <code>subject</code>, <code>date</code>, <code>message-id</code>. Override via <code>headersToSign</code>. Default canonicalization is <code>relaxed/relaxed</code> (most compatible).</p>',

  '<h2 id="calendar">Calendar invites <a class="anchor" href="#calendar">#</a></h2>',
  '<p>Pass <code>calendar: { method, icalText }</code> on any <code>send()</code>. The builder adds a <code>text/calendar; method=...</code> body part (alongside <code>text</code> / <code>html</code> in <code>multipart/alternative</code>) so Outlook, Gmail, and Apple Mail render it as an invite rather than a generic <code>.ics</code> attachment. Operators construct the iCalendar body per RFC 5545; the framework only validates that it begins with <code>BEGIN:VCALENDAR</code>.</p>',
